            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Macalister's ACTO, if correct (note earlier reading: OTTACI), may be related to the Old Irish verb <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/933">aigid</ref></foreign> ‘to lead, drive’ and the later attested name <foreign xml:lang="sga">Achtán</foreign>. The name ACTO also occurs in inscription I-COR-041 (Ballyknock, Co. Cork). The remaining start of the father's name may contain the adjective <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25369">gar</ref></foreign> ‘short’ or <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25380">garb</ref></foreign> ‘rough’ but it is impossible to be sure with so little surviving. Names such as <persName>Garbán</persName> and <persName>Garbith</persName> appear in later manuscript sources.</p>
            </div>
